		<msContents>
			<summary><bibl><ptr target="bib:IAR1969-1970"/></bibl> (no. 39, p. 50): <quote>This incomplete inscription in Tamil language and characters of the ninth century A.D., engraved on the <foreign>tripattakumuda</foreign> of the north and south walls of the Vaikuṇṭha Perumāḷ temple, is dated in the twenty-fifth year in the reign of Pallava Vijaya-Kampavarman. It mentions Cittiramēkataṭākam in Kaliyūr-kōttam and seems to record a gift of land endowed to a deity called Irunta-Perumāṉaṭikaḷ as <foreign>devadāna</foreign> and made tax-free for conducting a festival for seven days from Vicākam to Tiruvōṇam in the month of Vaikāci every year.</quote></summary>
		</msContents>
